From 48410d313f5957fab67a4c7d4879bbc5d31a2c23 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Ilya Gulya <ilya@gulya.me>
Date: Fri, 3 Jul 2026 00:21:07 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] perf#25a-hang (A0): fix kqchan proc-notification lost-wakeup
 deadlock

ROOT CAUSE (proven by the AUXLOG capture, tmp/a0_auxlog_HANG.txt): the brew
fork-storm hang is a lost-notification deadlock on the kqchan EVFILT_PROC channel.

When launchd tracks a build shell (pid 415) with NOTE_TRACK, every child fork
pushes a NOTE_FORK event onto that channel's server-side _events queue and asks
_sendNotification to ping the guest. The guest acks a notification by reading it
(evfilt_proc_copyout -> proc_read), which runs _read(): it sets
canSendNotification=true then deferNotification=true (defer so a new notification
can't overtake the read reply and desync the channel), sends the reply, then
calls _sendDeferredNotification to flush.

The defect: _sendNotification, when deferred, consumed _canSendNotification AND
stashed the ping into _deferredNotification, and _sendDeferredNotification only
re-sent an *already-stashed* Message. But _notify (event side, under _mutex) and
_read (ack side) serialize only on _notificationMutex, not in program order across
the split _mutex/_notificationMutex. Under the fork storm a _notify could stash
its ping *after* the _read that would have flushed it already ran -> the stash was
orphaned, canSendNotification stayed false, and every subsequent _notify was GATED
forever. The guest, never re-notified, never sent another proc_read, so
_sendDeferredNotification never ran again: permanent deadlock. The trace shows
exactly this -- channel id=259 frozen at canSendNotif=0 with _events climbing
24->36, no ACK for 27s, guest fd 39 holding one stale 12B notification, server
Send-Q=768 backed up. (This is NOT the perf#18 ring; both earlier ring fixes were
correctly falsified.)

FIX: make notification delivery level-triggered and self-healing.
  - _sendNotification when deferred no longer consumes the gate or stashes a
    Message; it just sets a sticky _notificationRequestedWhileDeferred flag.
  - _sendDeferredNotification, on clearing deferral, re-drives _sendNotification
    if a notification was owed OR the channel still _hasPendingEvents() (new
    virtual; Process overrides it to report a non-empty _events queue). The ping
    is contentless and duplicate-safe by design (guest reads, finds nothing, drops
    via 0xdead), so a spurious re-arm is harmless -- but a lost one can no longer
    deadlock. Lock order preserved (_mutex before _notificationMutex, never nested
    reversed; _notificationMutex dropped before _hasPendingEvents/_sendNotification).
  - A legacy-stash drain path is kept defensively.

Symmetric across both kqchan types (fix is in the shared base). Retains the
env-gated AUXLOG instrumentation from the previous commit for A/B verification.
Built from ~/work/darling-build; baseline 835946f9 backed up + restorable.
Pending: boot smoke + brew ring-ON A/B gate before this is declared GREEN.

Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.8 (1M context) <noreply@anthropic.com>
---
 internal-include/darlingserver/kqchan.hpp | 18 ++++++
 src/kqchan.cpp                            | 71 ++++++++++++++++++-----
 2 files changed, 75 insertions(+), 14 deletions(-)

diff --git a/internal-include/darlingserver/kqchan.hpp b/internal-include/darlingserver/kqchan.hpp
index a6847a4a3c85008da18e645540fe7b8e26039050..b7f93f560c3043f6ddaa25229c94683e10d433b9 100644
--- a/internal-include/darlingserver/kqchan.hpp
+++ b/internal-include/darlingserver/kqchan.hpp
@@ -42,6 +42,14 @@ namespace DarlingServer {
 		bool _canSendNotification = true;
 		bool _deferNotification = false;
 		std::optional<Message> _deferredNotification = std::nullopt;
+		// perf#25a-hang (A0): sticky "a notification was requested while deferred" flag. Replaces the
+		// orphan-prone _deferredNotification stash as the deferral carrier: a stashed Message could be
+		// left un-flushed if the _notify that stashed it raced past the _read that would flush it, and
+		// since _sendNotification also consumed _canSendNotification on the stash path, the channel then
+		// GATED every future notification forever (guest never re-notified -> never acks -> deadlock,
+		// exactly the brew fork-storm hang). A boolean is idempotent and self-healing: it is resolved
+		// every time deferral clears, and notifications are contentless + duplicate-safe by design.
+		bool _notificationRequestedWhileDeferred = false;
 		std::mutex _sendingMutex;
 		uint64_t _notificationCount = 0;
 
@@ -53,6 +61,12 @@ namespace DarlingServer {
 
 		virtual std::shared_ptr<Kqchan> sharedFromRoot();
 
+		// Whether the channel currently has pending work the peer should be notified about. Used by
+		// _sendDeferredNotification to re-arm a notification when deferral clears (level-triggered, so a
+		// notification lost to a defer/gate race is always recovered). Base returns false; the proc
+		// channel overrides it to report a non-empty event queue.
+		virtual bool _hasPendingEvents();
+
 		void _sendNotification();
 		void _sendDeferredNotification();
 
@@ -135,6 +149,10 @@ namespace DarlingServer {
 
 		virtual void _processMessages();
 
+		// perf#25a-hang (A0): report whether events remain to be read, so a notification lost to a
+		// defer/gate race is re-armed when deferral clears. Takes _mutex (the event-queue lock).
+		virtual bool _hasPendingEvents();
+
 		/**
 		 * See Kqchan::MachPort::_checkForEventsAsync(); this does the same thing for process kqchannels.
 		 */
diff --git a/src/kqchan.cpp b/src/kqchan.cpp
index 6752e27a766b7881e1ffe9ad6f38c44e5aa733a5..a49f0a7e33eb925957cad99e0e0353dab01f4b1c 100644
--- a/src/kqchan.cpp
+++ b/src/kqchan.cpp
@@ -239,6 +239,22 @@ void DarlingServer::Kqchan::_sendNotification() {
 		return;
 	}
 
+	// perf#25a-hang (A0): if notifications are currently deferred (a _read is in flight and will send
+	// its reply first, to keep channel messages in-order), DON'T consume _canSendNotification and DON'T
+	// stash a Message. Just record that a notification is owed. _sendDeferredNotification will re-drive
+	// _sendNotification once deferral clears, at which point it takes the real send path below. The old
+	// code consumed _canSendNotification here AND stashed into _deferredNotification; if the _read that
