 disposition/flush)

The guest-side capture (UPDATE 7) proved the brew hang is a lost/never-sent
DGRAM RPC reply: server idle, every parked guest thread in recvmsg with
Recv-Q=0. To name WHICH call and the exact drop site, add a per-guest-tid RPC
trace gated on the same DARLING_SERVER_AUXLOG=1 env (writes to the same
dserver-auxlog.txt so it interleaves chronologically with the kqchan AUXLOG).

Trace points, keyed by host tid + guest nsid so they line up with the
/proc/<tid> the hang capture sees parked:
  - call.cpp callFromMessage: RECV for every accepted call (incl s2c/push_reply)
  - thread.cpp pushCallReply: REPLY-DISP naming the 4 dispositions, plus
    SENT-UDS / SENT-RING at the actual send
  - call.cpp Call::sendReply: SENT-FALLBACK (thread-expired / error /
    push_reply direct re-send funnel), keyed by reply header number
  - both stash paths get a matching FLUSH: FLUSH-SAVED (interrupt_exit) and
    FLUSH-DEFERRED (s2c reply flush)
  - push_reply sub-paths: PUSHREPLY-STASH{pendingSaved,interruptTop},
    PUSHREPLY-DIRECT, and PENDINGSAVED->INTERRUPTTOP promotion

Stall signature reads straight off the tape: a RECV with no terminal SEND, or
a STASH with no matching FLUSH, names the stuck call + drop site.

Zero cost when the env is unset (one relaxed-load bool guard). Purely additive,
no behavior change on any path. NOT default-on; reverted before any
non-instrumented build. Builds clean (b600271b).

