Built + ran the env-gated per-tid RPC trace (8cb1c4e) at three reproduced hangs. Findings correct UPDATE 7:
  - Server is NOT frozen (replies_sent/messages_received advance; memberd polls every 5s) — UPDATE 7's
    "server idle" was a short-window artifact against memberd's slow cadence.
  - Every parked guest thread's LAST server event is a COMPLETED REPLY-DISP+SENT-UDS. No RECV-without-reply,
    no STASH-without-FLUSH. So no dropped/stranded RPC reply.
  - Server DGRAM listener Recv-Q = 0 (ss -x + /proc/net/unix) — the guest's request is NOT sitting unread,
    falsifying the EPOLLET missed-edge hypothesis.
  - All 3 launchd threads parked in recvmsg on the DGRAM band (Recv-Q=0); kqchan SEQPACKET Send-Q=768
    backlog persists but varies (2-7 channels) = downstream of launchd's kevent loop not running.
  - INTERMITTENT ~50% under instrumentation (one clean full build, next hung) => a timing race / lost
    wakeup, not a structural deadlock.

Two survivors, both point away from the server RPC drop path: (B') guest-side lost reply-wakeup (reply
left the server, guest recvmsg never woke) or (C') kqchan-drain circular wait. Resolving them needs the
guest DGRAM-band Recv-Q at the hang — the one gap is the dual-ns ss lookup mis-resolving autobind abstract
names for fds 8189-8191. NEXT is pure capture (read guest /proc/net/unix rx_queue by inode), no build.

Prod restored byte-identical to baseline 835946f9, west darling-doctor ALL GREEN. Trace lives on branch
fix/a0-kqchan-auxlog. Evidence + harnesses in job tmp (a0_rpctrace/launchd_anatomy/listener_recvq).

