+
+Instrumented the full psynch path (kern_synch.c: _psynch_cvwait entry/block, __psynch_cvsignal diff-gate + ksyn_cvsignal wake result, _psynch_mutexwait entry/prepost/block, _psynch_mutexdrop_internal entry + intr-post, ksyn_signal psynch_wait_wakeup return) AND the microthread layer (thread.c thread_unblock; thread.cpp Thread::resume). Ran on the signal-free repro cvstorm2 -DNCONS=1 -DNO_STORM. Findings at the freeze:
+
+- Steady state is a clean ping-pong on ONE mutex (0x100008068) + ONE condvar (0x1000080a8) between the 2 worker microthreads, seq advancing by PTHRW_INC (0x100) each iteration. cvsignal is always woke=1; KSYN_SIGNAL psynch_wait_wakeup always returns 0 (SUCCESS), NEVER 48 (NOT_WAITING). CV side is healthy.
+- The freeze is on the MUTEX. Last worker events: `MTX WAIT-block tid=B lseq=0xNN800` (a worker blocks on the mutex) immediately followed by `MTX DROP-enter tid=A ugen=0xNN800 nextgen=0xNN900 inq=1 firstwr=0xNN800` (the peer unlocks, SEES the waiter, inq=1) — and then NOTHING. No `UNBLOCK nstid=<B>`, no further worker op. The blocked worker is never woken; at shutdown it is resumed (proving it was asleep the whole time).
+- RESUME layer EXONERATED: `A0 RESUME DROPPED=0` (a wake is never lost because the target is neither running nor suspended); worker UNBLOCKs fire normally (2026 + 1370 across the run). The microthread suspend/resume `_resumePermit` machinery is NOT the bug.
+- => the lost wakeup is INSIDE `_psynch_mutexdrop_internal` (kern_synch.c ~597-645, non-firstfit branch): the unlocker computes the grant target `nextgen = ugen + PTHRW_INC`, then `low_writer == nextgen`? / `is_seqhigher(low_writer, nextgen)`? / else `ksyn_queue_find_seq(nextgen)`. In the freeze the single queued waiter's seq does NOT match `nextgen`, `find_seq` returns NULL, so it takes `prepost=true` — marks a preposted wakeup and wakes NOBODY, even though `inq=1` and the waiter is sitting right there. The waiter then waits forever; the unlocker returns to guest and eventually also blocks -> total stall (matches guest: work>0, both threads parked).
+- MTX DROP-intrpost=0 and MTX WAIT-recovered-intr=0 across the whole run: the kw_intr "interrupted wakeup" recovery machinery is NOT involved. This is a pure seq-matching miss in the normal grant path.
+
+STATUS: root cause layer PINNED — Apple psynch mutex-drop waiter-seq matching under duct-tape mis-selects the grant target for the actually-queued waiter and preposts instead of waking it (a genuine lost wakeup; deterministic; no signals). The `firstwr`(=ksynq_firstnum) snapshot in the trace is masked differently from the compare and can't by itself tell the failing iteration from the working ones (all 2703 inq=1 drops showed firstwr<nextgen, yet 3396 worker unblocks fired) — so the NEXT step is to trace INSIDE _psynch_mutexdrop_internal the exact branch taken (line604 signal / line614 prepost / line619 find_seq hit/miss) and the queued kwe's kwe_lockseq vs nextgen for the FAILING drop, to nail whether the bug is (a) an off-by-one in nextgen vs the waiter's registered lockseq, (b) is_seqhigher/is_seqlower wraparound at the 0x…00 boundary, or (c) the waiter enqueuing at the wrong seq in ksyn_wait. Then fix + gate boot -> cvstorm2 all-variants RESULT=OK 0 hang -> brew A/B 0 hang. Prod baseline 835946f9, doctor GREEN. Trace lives on branch as a diagnostic commit; repro tmp/cvstorm2.c, harness tmp/a0_cvtrace.sh.
