+## UPDATE 22 — ROOT CAUSE PINNED TO ONE LINE: Thread::doWork() drops a scheduled wake when the target is still _running (thread.cpp:488)
+
+CORRECTS UPDATE 21's "mutex seq-matching" guess. Traced the wake all the way down through every layer with the firstfit branch instrumented (the mutex is firstfit, so the real path is _psynch_mutexdrop_internal's firstfit branch, kern_synch.c ~572+: inq==0 -> prepost, inq>0 -> ksyn_mtxsignal(first waiter)). ksyn_mtxsignal_ret was ALWAYS 0/SUCCESS; DROP-intrpost / DROP-MISS / find_seq NEVER involved; CV side clean; RESUME DROPPED=0. So NOT the psynch protocol, NOT the seq-matching, NOT the resume permit.
+
+The lost wake is in the WORK-QUEUE DISPATCH. Instrumented Thread::doWork()'s early-return guards. At the freeze, exactly ONE anomaly in the whole run:
+    A0 DOWORK nstid=30 EARLY-RETURN already-running permit=0
+doWork() was invoked for a microthread pulled off the work queue (someone scheduleThread'd it) but hit `if (_running) { ...warn...; _rwlock.unlock(); return; }` (thread.cpp ~488). It returns WITHOUT running the microthread AND WITHOUT rescheduling it, and _resumePermit was already consumed (permit=0) -> the wake is SILENTLY DROPPED -> that microthread never runs again -> deadlock (guest: work>0, both workers parked, no signals — exactly the -DNCONS=1 -DNO_STORM repro).
+
+MECHANISM (the race): a microthread can be BOTH still-marked-_running (mid-transition through suspend()/doneWorking — _running is only cleared at the doneWorking tail, thread.cpp ~629) AND have a fresh work item queued by a waker. Even with DSERVER_SINGLE_THREADED, the WorkQueue keeps 1 PERMANENT worker but push() spawns TEMPORARY workers up to hardware_concurrency when _threadsAvailable==0 (workers.hpp:186) -> multiple OS threads drain the queue concurrently. The queued dispatch races the still-_running microthread: doWork() pops it, sees _running, bails without rescheduling. The reverse race (wake-before-suspend) is handled by _resumePermit; the "scheduled-while-still-_running -> doWork sees _running -> DROP" case has NO recovery.
