From c3f7b2b7da233269b44fa1e618488bd20e710cb9 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Ilya Gulya <ilya@gulya.me>
Date: Fri, 3 Jul 2026 07:23:36 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] perf#25a-hang (A0) FIX part 1: doWork() must not drop a
 dispatch that lands while the microthread is still _running

Root cause (UPDATE 22): Thread::doWork() popped a scheduled microthread but hit
`if (_running) return;` (thread.cpp) and returned WITHOUT running it and WITHOUT
rescheduling, while the resume permit was already consumed -> the wake delivered
via scheduleThread() was lost -> deadlock. The reverse race (wake-before-suspend)
is covered by _resumePermit; scheduled-while-_running had no recovery. The window
exists because _running clears only at the doneWorking tail, and WorkQueue::push()
spawns temporary OS workers up to hardware_concurrency even under
DSERVER_SINGLE_THREADED, so a waker on one OS thread can scheduleThread() a
microthread still _running on another.

FIX: doWork()'s _running guard records the owed re-run in a new _rerunPending
flag instead of dropping it; the doneWorking tail (after _running clears)
reschedules when _rerunPending is set. Crucially the _rerunPending reschedule is
NOT gated on _suspended (unlike _resumePermit): a dropped dispatch may be for a
pending CALL, not a suspended context, so gating on _suspended (the first attempt)
left the wake lost -- honor it whenever the thread is alive; doWork() no-ops
harmlessly if there is nothing to do.

GATED: boot smoke PASS; deterministic signal-free repro cvstorm2 -DNCONS=1
-DNO_STORM (and -DNO_STORM 8-consumer) now RESULT=OK (both HUNG on baseline).
KNOWN REMAINING: the signal-STORM variants (1cons_storm, full) still hang -- a
SEPARATE bug in the sigexc/interrupt-delivery path, addressed next. Prod restored
byte-identical baseline 835946f9.

