@@ -839,3 +839,15 @@ doWork() was invoked for a microthread pulled off the work queue (someone schedu
 MECHANISM (the race): a microthread can be BOTH still-marked-_running (mid-transition through suspend()/doneWorking — _running is only cleared at the doneWorking tail, thread.cpp ~629) AND have a fresh work item queued by a waker. Even with DSERVER_SINGLE_THREADED, the WorkQueue keeps 1 PERMANENT worker but push() spawns TEMPORARY workers up to hardware_concurrency when _threadsAvailable==0 (workers.hpp:186) -> multiple OS threads drain the queue concurrently. The queued dispatch races the still-_running microthread: doWork() pops it, sees _running, bails without rescheduling. The reverse race (wake-before-suspend) is handled by _resumePermit; the "scheduled-while-still-_running -> doWork sees _running -> DROP" case has NO recovery.
 
 FIX DIRECTION (gate boot FIRST): doWork()'s `if (_running)` branch must NOT silently drop the dispatch. Set a pending-reschedule marker under _rwlock so the doneWorking tail (which already re-checks _resumePermit && _suspended to reschedule, thread.cpp ~634) reschedules once _running clears; OR make the run-loop re-enqueue on this collision. Invariant: "a scheduleThread that lands while _running causes exactly one more doWork after _running clears." Keep minimal; gate: boot smoke -> cvstorm2 -DNCONS=1 -DNO_STORM + all variants RESULT=OK 0/N hang -> brew reinstall A/B 0 hang. bd7cdb9/5766b1d target unrelated layers; 65038e3 (uninit mutex_link) stays. Prod baseline 835946f9, doctor GREEN. Diagnostic traces on branch; repro tmp/cvstorm2.c, harness tmp/a0_cvtrace.sh.
+
+## UPDATE 23 — FIX PART 1 LANDED (signal-free lost wake fixed & gated); a SECOND, storm-only bug remains
+
+Implemented the UPDATE 22 fix (darlingserver 57b86c8): Thread::doWork()'s `if (_running)` guard now records `_rerunPending` instead of silently dropping the dispatch, and the doneWorking tail reschedules on it. CRITICAL detail found during bring-up: the `_rerunPending` reschedule must NOT be gated on `_suspended` (the first attempt gated `resumeAfterWorking` on `_suspended` and STILL hung — trace showed `DONEWORK nstid=30 rerunPending=1 susp=0 -> resched=0`, i.e. the dropped dispatch was for a pending CALL, not a suspended context). Corrected gate: `((_resumePermit && _suspended) || _rerunPending) && !_terminating && !_dead`.
+
+GATE RESULTS (build b58c6c90, boot smoke PASS):
+  cvstorm2 -DNCONS=1 -DNO_STORM  => RESULT=OK   (baseline: HANG)   ✅ fixed
+  cvstorm2 -DNO_STORM (8 cons)   => RESULT=OK   (baseline: HANG)   ✅ fixed
+  cvstorm2 -DNCONS=1 (storm)     => RESULT=HANG                    ❌ still hangs
+  cvstorm2 (full, storm)         => no-result                     ❌
+
+=> The SIGNAL-FREE lost wake is genuinely fixed (Part 1, committed 57b86c8). But a SECOND, DISTINCT bug lives in the SIGNAL-STORM path. Storm census on the Part-1 fix (cvstorm2 -DNCONS=1, SIGUSR1 no-SA_RESTART hammering the consumer): the consumer wedges almost immediately (done=300 frozen, work climbs to 649M, storm_hits=100K, c0=300). So the SIGCHLD-equivalent storm breaks the consumer's cond_wait recovery — this IS the sigexc/interrupt-abort territory from UPDATE 14-19 (which was a red herring for the signal-free case but is REAL for the storm case). Mechanism to pin next: SIGUSR1 -> interrupt_enter RPC -> dtape_thread_sigexc_enter -> clear_wait_internal(THREAD_INTERRUPTED) aborts the ksyn_wait; the psynch_cvcontinue/psynch_mtxcontinue continuation runs with THREAD_INTERRUPTED; the guest re-issues cvwait (EINTR) but a wakeup is lost across the abort. Note brew's real workload HAS the SIGCHLD storm, so Part 1 alone is necessary-but-not-sufficient for the brew hang; Part 2 (storm path) is required for the zero-hang criterion. NEXT: instrument the interrupt-abort + psynch_cvcontinue path on cvstorm2 -DNCONS=1 (storm) to find the lost wake across the sigexc abort. Prod restored byte-identical baseline 835946f9; Part 1 on branch @ 57b86c8.

From 8a6fd828ca8e189b64fa185536fa0ebf46cfa634 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Ilya Gulya <ilya@gulya.me>
Date: Fri, 3 Jul 2026 08:08:50 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] perf#25a-hang (A0) FIX part 2a: eliminate the psynch
 grant-clobber race under signal storm

Two coupled duct-tape fixes that together eliminate the mtxcontinue lost-grant
class (measured: clobber detector 0/0 across storm runs after this change; the
signal-free variants stay OK and boot smoke passes):

1. thread_unblock() now finalizes the wait-state transition (clear TH_WAIT|TH_UNINT,
   set TH_RUN) exactly as XNU does, instead of leaving TH_WAIT set until the
   microthread physically resumed via dtape_thread_entering(). This closes the
   window where a racing clear_wait_internal(THREAD_INTERRUPTED) saw TH_WAIT still
   set and re-fired thread_go().

2. dtape_thread_sigexc_enter() no longer pre-assigns wait_result = THREAD_INTERRUPTED
   before clear_wait_internal(). clear_wait_internal() -> thread_go() writes the
   result itself, but ONLY when the thread is genuinely still waiting. The
   unconditional pre-assignment clobbered an already-committed THREAD_AWAKENED psynch
   grant, so psynch_mtxcontinue took its EINTR error path and discarded an
   already-dequeued mutex grant (kwe_psynchretval) -> guest re-waits on an empty
   queue -> deadlock (intermittent brew SIGCHLD-storm hang).

Deterministic proof: cvstorm2 -DNCONS=1 (storm on) went from freezing at
done<=5390 (grant lost every few thousand ops) to running 50k+ ops with the mutex
clobber gone. Repro/gate in tests/../tmp/{cvstorm2.c,a0_storm_repeat.sh}.

RESIDUAL (NOT fixed here): storm variants still hang intermittently (~3/10) via a
DIFFERENT mechanism -- a CV-wait EINTR whose interrupt reply appears not to reach
the guest (thread returns idle to the server but never re-issues cvwait/mutexwait),
i.e. the interrupt-reply-routing / dropped-RPC class, not psynch. Tracked as
part 2b. USER CRITERION is zero hangs, so A0 remains open.

Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.8 (1M context) <noreply@anthropic.com>
---
 duct-tape/src/thread.c | 34 +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++-
 1 file changed, 33 insertions(+), 1 deletion(-)

diff --git a/duct-tape/src/thread.c b/duct-tape/src/thread.c
index 1e40f09c0df095f76832b6e26571184ed0570be0..a0009e8e299435e1ca9a88057e1139d3d4c80160 100644
--- a/duct-tape/src/thread.c
+++ b/duct-tape/src/thread.c
@@ -500,7 +500,20 @@ void dtape_thread_sigexc_enter(dtape_thread_t* thread) {
 	// transition matches XNU, where a signal-interrupted wait is torn down by
 	// thread_go(), not by the caller hand-clearing TH_WAIT. (perf#25a A0)
 	thread->xnu_thread.state &= ~TH_UNINT;
-	thread->xnu_thread.wait_result = THREAD_INTERRUPTED;
+	// perf#25a A0 (Part 2): do NOT pre-assign wait_result here. clear_wait_internal()
+	// -> thread_go() -> thread_unblock() writes wait_result = THREAD_INTERRUPTED itself,
+	// but ONLY when it actually finds the thread still waiting (TH_WAIT set). If a psynch
+	// grant already unblocked this thread (thread_wakeup_thread -> thread_unblock set
+	// wait_result = THREAD_AWAKENED and cleared TH_WAIT) but its microthread continuation
+	// has not yet physically run, an unconditional assignment here CLOBBERS that committed
+	// THREAD_AWAKENED grant to THREAD_INTERRUPTED. The continuation (psynch_mtxcontinue)
+	// then takes its error path and returns EINTR, discarding an already-dequeued mutex
+	// grant (kwe_psynchretval) -- the guest re-issues the wait against an empty queue and
+	// deadlocks (the intermittent brew SIGCHLD-storm hang; repro cvstorm2 -DNCONS=1 storm).
+	// Letting clear_wait_internal own the write matches XNU (clear_wait(THREAD_INTERRUPTED)
+	// only rouses a thread that is genuinely still waiting) and leaves an already-delivered
+	// wakeup intact. Paired with thread_unblock() finalizing TH_WAIT->TH_RUN so the
+	// second (racing) abort correctly sees the thread no longer waiting.
 	clear_wait_internal(&thread->xnu_thread, THREAD_INTERRUPTED);
 	thread_unlock(&thread->xnu_thread);
 };
@@ -616,6 +629,25 @@ wait_result_t thread_block(thread_continue_t continuation) {
 // thread locked
 boolean_t thread_unblock(thread_t xthread, wait_result_t wresult) {
 	dtape_thread_t* thread = dtape_thread_for_xnu_thread(xthread);
+
+	// perf#25a A0 (Part 2): finalize the wait-state transition here, matching XNU's
+	// thread_unblock() which clears TH_WAIT|TH_UNINT and sets TH_RUN. Duct-tape
+	// previously left TH_WAIT set until the microthread physically resumed and ran
+	// dtape_thread_entering(). That left a window: after a psynch grant delivered its
+	// wakeup via thread_go()->thread_unblock() (wait_result = THREAD_AWAKENED) but
+	// before the queued microthread actually ran, a racing signal abort
+	// (dtape_thread_sigexc_enter -> clear_wait_internal(THREAD_INTERRUPTED)) still saw
+	// (state & (TH_WAIT|TH_TERMINATE)) == TH_WAIT and re-fired thread_go(), CLOBBERING
+	// wait_result to THREAD_INTERRUPTED. The continuation (psynch_mtxcontinue) then took
+	// its error path and returned EINTR, THROWING AWAY an already-committed mutex grant
+	// (kwe_psynchretval, dequeued from the kwq) -- the guest re-issues the wait against a
+	// now-empty queue and deadlocks (the intermittent brew SIGCHLD-storm hang; repro
+	// cvstorm2 -DNCONS=1 storm-on). Clearing TH_WAIT here makes the second
+	// clear_wait_internal correctly return KERN_NOT_WAITING and leave the grant intact.
+	// (Do not clear TH_TERMINATE: a terminating thread must stay terminating.)
+	thread->xnu_thread.state &= ~(TH_WAIT | TH_UNINT);
+	thread->xnu_thread.state |= TH_RUN;
+
 	thread->xnu_thread.wait_result = wresult;
 
 	// Cancel the wait timer if one was armed for a timed wait. XNU's

From 760bb9b91825d223d834ab99437185233259e715 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Ilya Gulya <ilya@gulya.me>
